Breakfast - Pre flashback
Loving part - early morning, waking up, cosy, romantic


Bedroom
Every morning, I would awake to the smell of hot cocoa that came from the kitchen.
Our room was warm, bathed in sunlight.
There was an empty spot in bed, right to where I lay, still full of Amélie’s shape.
# bedroom bg
# afficher le sprite de la dom vers la droite

Before we met, we both had trouble waking up in the morning.
Every day, I would hit the snooze button on my alarm, only to do it again ten minutes later. I didn’t want to leave the comfort of my bed, the warmth of the sheets, or my half-forgotten dreams.
I didn’t even sleep well after the first alarm : there can be no rest when you know you’re dallying and should already be on your way. At the back of my mind, I always thought about the time I had left before the next alarm.
I would feel exhausted before I had even set a foot on the floor.



After I met Amélie – no, when we woke up together at the sound of a common alarm, hugging each other in the same bed – it became easier. The weight of fatigue didn’t disappear all of a sudden (for love cannot cure one's health), but I had a reason to stay awake.
In those days, I want to believe that I was happy.


Even when our rhythms diverged[a], I kept my drive. Although I would have loved to cuddle with Amélie, to bury myself in her in hopes that we would merge together forever more, I could rise with ease, so appealing was the prospect to join the one I loved and enjoy her cooking.
