Introspection: Leïla’s past relationships
Ambiance: introspection, thinking about the past… loneliness, dysphoria.
Amélie was right when she said I was gentle and soft. I care for my partners. I love them, I want them to feel cherished. This has led me to fulfilling the roles they expect of me: most often, this meant I was a top.


I am quite tall, and, as a result, many girls have told me that they wanted me to step on them. Between this, the expectations people have of a trans woman and the tendency of many transgender girls to be subby bottoms, it was the norm for me to lead in bed. To be active, to take.
I never really questioned this: it felt so natural to have that role. When I said that I did what my partners wanted of me, I did not mean that they actually told me that this was what they desired or expected: it was simply the course of things. I had always been a top, and I had never really thought of being anything else.
I had grown up surrounded by such assumptions, after all: back when people assumed I was a boy, I was often praised for my height or my broad shoulders. I was told I would probably grow up to be a ladykiller. And girls did notice me. I was asked out several times, or pushed into relationships - I could never really understand why. But I followed what was expected of me… and I played the boyfriend’s part. I learnt how to act.
I remember being told that I slouched too much, back when I was a teenager. In retrospect, I think that I was trying to make myself look small. Dysphoria ensured I grew up looking at the ground.
I felt too masculine. I didn’t act masculine enough.


People didn’t expect me to transition.
I was not that tall for a boy, but I have had many remarks about it now that I am seen as a woman. To me, it is a point of dysphoria.
So, it came as a surprise when lesbians praised me for my height, even before I came to Paris. I distinctly remember that time, at the meet-up, where I had told that I was looking to make friends and someone joked that it would not take long for me to break some hearts with how tall I was.
For some reason, it did not feel good at all.
It felt… othering. Like I was receiving the same kind of compliments that I had received before. Like what was loved were precisely the parts of me that made me feel less of a woman.
I grew to accept them more. Still. I never quite felt seen. It is not like lesbian love can help me forget the way passersby look at me when I walk in the street.
